<h2>Thursday, December 29</h2>

<p>Today we went to see the Hassan II Mosque, one of the largest and one of the few open to non-Muslims. The mosque is magnificent, impressive, and beautiful. Since we were early, we walked around the outside, waiting for the tour time. The whole building is adorned to the millimeter. There are details on every single surface of the building, in an out, including the ceilings, doors, arches, walls, floor, fountains, steps, lamps… everything is intricate and beautiful. After getting our tickets and figuring out which group to join (they were grouped by language), we finally entered the mosque. The ticket includes a plastic bag for your shoes, which should be removed when entering the Prayer Hall. There are no words to describe the intricacy, beauty, and opulence of the mosaic, wood, plaster, metal, and glass work (please zoom in the pictures). And the size of it. We saw the prayer areas for men (main floor) and women (smaller upper balconies), then exited the prayer hall to see the ablutions area, with fountains and faucets. We then tried to get a taxi to the Corniche (the resort beach area) but the prices we were given were too high. We then tried just to get back to the hotel area, but the prices were still too much. We walked a bit until we found a driver willing to take us back for a semi-decent price. We were starving, as it was close to 4 pm (with only a croissant and a café) when we ate at a place recommended by the guide book: Dolphin Tavern. We had seafood. It was just ok, but pricy. We walked in and around the Medina, looking at shops. / <span class="spanish">Hoy fuimos a ver la mezquita de Hassan II, una de las más grandes y de las pocas accesibles a gente no musulmana. Todo en la mezquita es impresionante, opulenta, bello. En lo que esperábamos la hora del tour, admiramos las fachadas del edificio. Cada milímetro de la mezquita está repleta de detalles (aumenta el zoom en las fotos): desde techos, puertas, arcos, paredes, pisos, fuentes, escalones y lámparas… todo es increíblemente elaborado. Ya con boletos y en el tour en español, entramos a la mezquita, donde nos quitamos los zapatos (nos dieron bolsas de plástico para cargarlos) y admiramos la Sala de Oraciones, con área separada para hombres (en el piso principal) y mujeres (en los pequeños balcones laterales). Después fuimos a la zona de baños, pues se deben lavar antes de orar. Al salir tratamos de negociar precios de taxis a la zona de la playa, pero estaba muy caro. Hasta la tarifa de regreso al hotel estaba carísima y tardamos en hallar un taxista que nos diera precio decente. Ya eran como las 4 de la tarde y no habíamos comido, así que decidimos ir a un restaurante de mariscos recomendado en la guía. Comimos pulpos a la gallega, calamar y almejas. Como el restaurante estaba afuera de la Medina, entramos a algunos puestos a bobear. </span></p>

