<h2>Friday, December 30</h2>

<p>We woke up late and went out searching for couscous. We read that this dish is prepared on Fridays, prayer day. We found Costa Brava, a restaurant nearby, where we shared a plate of couscous with chicken and vegetables, and a tagine with lamb and dried plums. Both were amazing and affordable at about 12 USD (115 DH). We then walked around the shoe district and got lost wandering in an out of shops and blocks, and admiring the art deco buildings. We saw shop areas with fabrics, flowers, perfumes, clothing, spices, a market (we bought saffron). We also bought some blocks of candy (turrón) from a lady on a street cart, who had to show us with her coins how much to pay her (14DH). We drank mint tea, their traditional drink, at a café. Then, some more shopping. At the plaza we bought and ate a phyllo pastry from a street vendor. We then went to the bar at the Hyatt across the street, to have a drink. / <span class="spanish">Nos levantamos tarde y salimos a buscar cuscus, un platillo de semolina que leímos se prepara los Viernes, el dia de oración (equivalente al Domingo católico). Lo hallamos en el restaurante Costa Brava: compartimos un cuscus de pollo y verduras y un tajin de borrego con ciruelas pasas. Ambos estuvieron deliciosos y salieron baratos. De ahí caminamos por los barrios cercanos, los cuales se dividen por tipos de mercancías: zapatos, telas, flores, perfumes, ropa, especies, y hasta entramos a un mercadito. En la calle le compramos a una señora unos turrones usando señas. Ella agarró cambio para mostrarnos cuánto debíamos pagar. Descansamos en un café y tomamos té de menta con azúcar, la bebida tradicional de ahí. Luego de bobear un poco más, de admirar las fachadas de los 1930s de los edificios, y de probar una empanada callejera, fuimos al bar del hotel Hyatt por unas bebidas.</span></p>

